      • openForCreate

        public abstract OutputStream openForCreate()
        Open the file for writing. If the file already exists, it is truncated. If the file doesn't exist, it is created. Note that the current JSimple file I/O model is that files, when written, are completely rewritten.
        Returns:
        output stream, to write the file contents

        public OutputStream openForCreateAtomic()

      • openForCreateAtomic

        public OutputStream openForCreateAtomic(long lastModifiedTime)
        Open the file for writing/creating, replacing the current file if it already exists.

        All writes are first made to a temp file (filename + "-temp" suffix, in the same directory). When the returned stream is closed, the new file is committed by renaming the -temp file to the original. That way, the file is either completely updated or not updated at all, never left in a half-updated state.

        If lastModifiedTime is non-zero, then it's set as the last modified time on the file, as part of the atomic update (the timestamp is set on the temp file first & preserved on the rename).

        Parameters:
        lastModifiedTime - modification time in millis, set on updated file; ignored if zero
        Returns:
        OutputStream, with a close handler attached to update the original file when closed

        public abstract void delete()

      • exists

        public abstract boolean exists()
        See if the file exists. If there's an error checking if the file exists, this method throws an exception when possible, though for some platform implementations it'll just return false if platform can't distinguish not existing from there being an error checking.
        Returns:
        true if the file exists

      • getLastModifiedTime

        public abstract long getLastModifiedTime()
        Get the last modified / last write timestamp of this file. Of the 3 file timestamps (created, modified, and accessed) on files, modified is most important in Windows. It's the one displayed by default with the "dir" command and shown in file details in Explorer. It's also the timestamp used for most other applications. So that's the timestamp that JSimple best supports querying and changing.
        Returns:
        last modified timestamp for file

      • setLastModifiedTime

        public abstract void setLastModifiedTime(long time)
        Set the last modified / last write timestamp of this file. Of the 3 file timestamps (created, modified, and accessed) on files, modified is most important in Windows. It's the one displayed by default with the "dir" command and shown in file details in Explorer. It's also the timestamp used for most other applications. So that's the timestamp that JSimple best supports querying and changing.
        Parameters:
        time - time in millis (milliseconds since Jan 1, 1970 UTC)
